&lt;/ol&gt;</description></item><item><title>Cut Through the Noise: XDR’s Key to Exposing Real Threats with Correlated Context</title><link>https://justrwx.github.io/blog/connecting-the-dots-xdr/</link><pubDate>Mon, 15 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://justrwx.github.io/blog/connecting-the-dots-xdr/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;XDR (Extended Detection and Response) isn’t a silver bullet — it’s the glue that turns isolated alerts into a single, actionable incident by correlating telemetry across email, endpoint, and network. This reduces time-to-detection and enables faster containment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img
class="my-0 rounded-md"
loading="lazy"
decoding="async"
fetchpriority="low"
alt="Flow diagram showing email → endpoint → network correlation forming a single incident"
src="https://justrwx.github.io/images/xdr-context.svg"
&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;h2 class="relative group"&gt;Context First: Making XDR Actionable
&lt;div id="context-first-making-xdr-actionable" class="anchor"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none"&gt;
&lt;a class="text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline" href="#context-first-making-xdr-actionable" aria-label="Anchor"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In my first post, I wrote about arriving in the SOC and learning that real threats rarely appear as textbook CVEs. Often, the biggest risk is not a clever zero-day — it’s noise: dozens of isolated alerts with no shared context.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Beyond EDR: Why Your Cybersecurity Strategy Is Failing</title><link>https://justrwx.github.io/blog/cs-beyond-edr/</link><pubDate>Mon, 24 Nov 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://justrwx.github.io/blog/cs-beyond-edr/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;At my last job, I heard a phrase that stopped me in my tracks:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Everything is fine. We have an EDR solution, and we&amp;rsquo;ve never had an incident.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This statement sounded reassuring on the surface, but the reality was dangerously different.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 class="relative group"&gt;The True Scope of Responsibility
&lt;div id="the-true-scope-of-responsibility" class="anchor"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none"&gt;
&lt;a class="text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline" href="#the-true-scope-of-responsibility" aria-label="Anchor"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As a support engineer, my role extends far beyond &amp;ldquo;fixing machines&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;blocking emails.&amp;rdquo; My core mission is to &lt;strong&gt;ensure the operational continuity of the entire organization&lt;/strong&gt;. This means every workstation, server, peripheral, and application must function as a cohesive, well-oiled part of a larger system.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>My First Month in a SOC: From CVEs to Real Threats</title><link>https://justrwx.github.io/blog/first-post/</link><pubDate>Fri, 14 Nov 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://justrwx.github.io/blog/first-post/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;My first month in the Security Operations Center (SOC) felt like drinking from a firehose. Between the blinking dashboards, the constant stream of alerts, and the alphabet soup of acronyms, it was a lot to take in. But then, a real-world threat popped up on my screen, and suddenly, the theory I had been learning snapped into sharp focus. It all started with a CVE.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3 class="relative group"&gt;What’s in a Name? The Reality of a CVE
&lt;div id="whats-in-a-name-the-reality-of-a-cve" class="anchor"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none"&gt;
&lt;a class="text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline" href="#whats-in-a-name-the-reality-of-a-cve" aria-label="Anchor"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Before working in a SOC, I knew what a &lt;strong&gt;CVE (Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures)&lt;/strong&gt; was—a unique ID for a known vulnerability. But it was just a number, an entry in a database. It wasn&amp;rsquo;t until I saw one in the wild that I truly understood its power.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>